  "opinion": "As a man who's spent most of his life working with hands and building things in Bari, Italy, I've never really thought about the gender gap in science as a formal issue. My father had a PhD and my mother a master's, so I grew up surrounded by people who valued learning, but I never saw it as a divide between genders. When I was a kid, we'd talk about how science is about understanding the world—whether it's fixing a leaky pipe or building a bridge. That's the kind of practical science that matters to me, and it's something everyone can do, regardless of gender. I think the real gap isn't about who can do science, but about who gets to be seen as capable. In my community, we don't have the same conversations about gender roles as we do in the tech world or academia. For instance, when my daughter asks me about her science projects, I encourage her to think about how her ideas can help people in her town, not just in a lab. The gap, I believe, is more about the way we talk about science and who we let into the conversation. We should address it by making science accessible to everyone, starting with the basics—like teaching kids to ask questions through hands-on projects. If we can get kids to see science as part of their everyday life, the gap will shrink naturally. I don't think we need to change the system too much; we just need to make sure that everyone feels they belong in the process of discovery.",
